      <title>Pesticides could wipe out wild bees, study says</title>
      <description><![CDATA[Contact inquiries@nextanimation.com.tw to license this or any News Direct videoFor story suggestions please contact tips@nextanimation.com.twRESTRICTIONS: NONEPopular pesticides used on common crops prevent bees from laying eggs and could eventually cause bee populations to die out, a new study says.A group of pesticides known as neonicotinoids [a]are used on some of the most commonly grown crops in the U.S., including corn, soybean and canola.Bumblebee queens exposed to the neonicotinoid thiamethoxam [b]under laboratory conditions were 26 percent less likely to lay eggs, according to a study published in the journal Nature Ecology & Evolution.The study said that other factors in the wild, such as loss of wildflowers, parasites, or climate change may also have a harmful impact on bee populations.The results of the study are likely to lead to further calls to restrict the use of pesticides, NPR reported. Neonicotinoids were temporarily banned in the European Union in 2013. RUNDOWN SHOWS:1. Neonicotinoid pesticides like thiamethoxam sprayed on crops including corn, soybean, canola 2. Bees come into contact with pesticide3. Bees exposed to thiamethoxam 26 percent less likely to lay eggs4. Factors in declining bee populations include pesticides, loss of wildflowers, parasites, climate changeVOICEOVER (in English): "A group of pesticides known as neonicotinoids [c]are used on some of the most commonly grown crops in the U.S., including corn, soybean and canola.""According to a study in the UK, the neonicotinoid thiamethoxam [d]is harmful to bee populations.""The study showed that in laboratory conditions, bumblebee queens exposed to the pesticide were 26 percent less likely to lay eggs.""However, the study said that other factors in the wild, such as loss of wildflowers, parasites, or climate change may also have a harmful impact on bee populations."SOURCES: Nature Ecology & Evolution, NPR, The Guardianhttp://go.nature.com/2w60FZa http://n.pr/