      <title>Asphalt mixed with cigarette butts could pave the way to a greener future</title>
      <description><![CDATA[Contact inquiries@nextanimation.com to license this or any News Direct videoFor story suggestions please contact tips@nextanimation.com.twRESTRICTIONS: NONEScientists in Australia have come up with a way of putting cigarette butts to good use, by using them to build roads and sidewalks.Cigarette butts are made of cellulose acetate and contain a cocktail of toxic chemicals. Trillions of butts are thrown away each year, entering waterways and poisoning wildlife.Researchers at the Royal Melbourne Institute of Technology (RMIT) encapsulated cigarette butts with bitumen [a]and paraffin wax to lock in the toxic chemicals, according to a news release on the RMIT website.They then mixed the encapsulated cigarette butts with hot asphalt to make a sample road-building material.The material reduces thermal conductivity and can handle heavy traffic, according to the researchers.If the material is adopted and proves a success, it could benefit the environment by reducing cigarette butt pollution and cooling down cities.The research was carried out by the same team that last year showed a way of making clay bricks with cigarette butts to help solve the issue of littering.  RUNDOWN SHOWS:1. Cigarette butts made of plastic, contain toxins; discarded into environment, harm wildlife2. Cigarette butts encapsulated with bitumen and paraffin wax to lock in the chemicals3. Encapsulated cigarette butts mixed with hot asphalt mix to make samples of road-building material4. Material can handle heavy traffic and reduces thermal conductivityVOICEOVER (in English): "Cigarette butts are made of cellulose acetate and contain a cocktail of toxic chemicals. Trillions of butts are thrown away each year, entering waterways and poisoning wildlife.""Researchers in Australia encapsulated cigarette butts with bitumen [b]and paraffin wax to lock in the toxic chemicals.""They then mixed the encapsulated cigarette butts with hot asphalt to make a sample road-building material.""According to the researchers, the material reduces thermal conductivity and can handle heavy traffic."SOURCES: RMIT, ScienceDirect https://www.rmit.edu.au/news/all-news/2017/aug/how-to-pave-over-our-big-butt-problemhttp://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S0950061817314241?via%3Dihub***For story suggestions please contact tips@nextanimation.com.twFor technical and editorial support, please contact:Asia: +61 2 93 73 1841Europe: +44 20 7542 7599Americas and Latam: +1 800 738 8377]]></description>
