      <title>Blue light from electronic devices has negative impact on sleep, study says</title>
      <description><![CDATA[Contact inquiries@nextanimation.com to license this or any News Direct videoFor story suggestions please contact tips@nextanimation.com.twRESTRICTIONS: NONELooking at digital devices at night could be ruining our sleep, according to the authors of a new study.Blue light emitted by electronic devices has a detrimental effect on sleep quality, researchers from the University of Houston report, in a study published in Ophthalmic & Physiological Optics.Blue light is also emitted by the sun. It activates retinal ganglion cells in the eyes that suppress the body's production of melatonin, the hormone that regulates sleep.The study found that subjects who wore glasses to block blue light at night experienced a 50 per cent increase in melatonin levels and reported better sleep.The authors of the study recommend people should wear blue light-blocking glasses at night and switch electronic devices to night mode to improve the quality of their sleep.RUNDOWN SHOWS:1. Blue light emitted by electronic devices2. Blue light emitted by the sun, activates ganglion cells to suppress melatonin3. Study shows wearing blue light filter glasses raises melatonin levels 50 percent4. Study authors recommend wearing blue light filter glasses to watch TV at night; switch devices to night mode.VOICEOVER (in English): "According to a study, blue light emitted by electronic devices, including smartphones, tablets and flat-screen TVs, has a detrimental effect on sleep quality.""Blue light is also emitted by the sun. It activates cells in the eyes that suppress the body's production of melatonin, the hormone that regulates sleep.""The study found that subjects who wore glasses to block blue light at night experienced a 50 per cent increase in melatonin levels, and reported better sleep.""The authors of the study recommend people should wear blue light-blocking glasses at night and switch electronic devices to night mode."SOURCES: Ophthalmic and Physiological Optics, Unive