      <title>How North Korean missiles could be stopped from reaching Guam</title>
      <description><![CDATA[Contact inquiries@nextanimation.com to license this or any News Direct videoFor story suggestions please contact tips@nextanimation.com.twRESTRICTIONS: NONEThe U.S. and its military allies in Asia are preparing for a potential North Korean missile strike at Guam. The U.S., South Korea and Japan have several lines of defense against North Korean missiles, including the Aegis [a]and THAAD anti-ballistic missile defense systems.North Korea plans to launch four missiles into waters near Guam on August 15, if Kim Jong-un gives the go ahead. THAAD systems in South Korea could track the missiles by radar, but would not be able to intercept them in space on their trajectory to Guam, according to the New York Times.The trajectory of the North Korean missiles may also carry them past Japanese Aegis ships in the Sea of Japan. However, U.S. Aegis ships stationed in the western Pacific would stand a better chance of interception.The last line of defense is the THAAD missile defense system on Guam. The system has a good record in tests, but has never been tested in a real-world scenario.  RUNDOWN SHOWS:1. Location of anti-missile defenses2. North Korea missile launch; tracked by THAAD in South Korea3. Japanese and U.S. Aegis ships fire missiles4. THAAD system on Guam intercepts North Korean missileVOICEOVER (in English): "The U.S., South Korea and Japan have several lines of defense against North Korean missiles, including the Aegis [b]and THAAD anti-ballistic missile defense systems.""North Korea plans to launch four missiles at waters near Guam. THAAD systems in South Korea could track the missiles by radar, but would not be able to intercept them in space on their trajectory to Guam.""The trajectory of the North Korean missiles may also carry them past Japanese Aegis ships in the sea of Japan. However, U.S. Aegis ships stationed in the western Pacific would stand a better chance of interception." "The last line of defense is the THAAD missile defense system on Guam. The system has a good record in tests, but has never been tested in a real-world scenario."SOURCES: New York Times, CNNhttps://www.nytimes.com/2017/08/11/world/asia/guam-north-korea-missile-defense.htmlhttp://edition.cnn.com/2017/08/13/asia/north-korea-guam-trump/index.html***For story suggestions please contact tips@nextanimation.com.twFor technical and editorial support, please contact:Asia: +61 2 93 73 1841Europe: +44 20 7542 7599Americas and Latam: +1 800 738 8377]]></description>
