      <title>Amazon patents mobile delivery drone fulfillment centers</title>
      <description><![CDATA[Contact inquiries@nextanimation.com to license this or any News Direct videoFor story suggestions please contact tips@nextanimation.com.twRESTRICTIONS: NONEAmazon recently patented a network of mobile drone delivery hubs that can deliver items from moving workstations based on trains, boats and trucks.Dubbed the "intermodal vehicle" in its patent document,  the mobile hubs look similar to shipping containers, with fulfillment centers inside. They are also equipped with drone maintenance facilities that change battery or replace motors or propellers.The vehicles can be loaded on moving trains, ships and trucks and can move to places with high demand. Amazon environs a network of mobile fulfillment centers which could cut the costs of building fixed warehouses.However, there is no guarantee that Amazon is really going forward with this system. UPS, on the other hand, has already tested drone delivery from its trucks.RUNDOWN SHOWS:1. Amazon's intermodal vehicle2. A drone deployed from a moving train3. A network of mobile fulfillment centers4. The system fitted on a ship and a truckVOICEOVER (in English): "Amazon's intermodal vehicles look similar to shipping containers, with fulfillment centers inside and drone maintenance equipments.""The vehicles can be loaded on moving trains, which are equipped with drones to deliver the items." "Amazon environs a network of mobile fulfillment centers which could cut the costs of building fixed warehouses.""The system could also be fitted on ships and trucks."SOURCES: New Atlas, Business Insider, Puget Sound Business Journal, The Verge, US Patent and Trademark Officehttp://newatlas.com/amazon-drone-delivery-train-repairs/50781/https://www.businessinsider.com.au/amazon-patents-mobile-drone-stations-on-trains-vans-boats-2017-8?utm_source=feedly&utm_medium=webfeeds&r=US&IR=Thttps://www.bizjournals.com/seattle/news/2017/08/01/amazon-patents-delivery-drone-fulfillment-centers.htmlhttps://www.theverge.com/2017