      <title>Green tea compound may protect sensitive teeth</title>
      <description><![CDATA[Contact inquiries@nextanimation.com to license this or any News Direct videoFor story suggestions please contact tips@nextanimation.com.twRESTRICTIONS: NONEResearchers from China's Wuhan University have found a new way to treat sensitive teeth using a green tea extract.Teeth may become sensitive when tooth enamel gets worn off, which exposes the dentin tissue underneath. Food or bacteria that comes into contact with nerve endings through the tubules in dentin tissue is what causes pain.A group of researchers led by Cui Huang of Wuhan University combined a green tea polyphenol called epigallocatechin-3-gallate, or EGCG, with a mineral called nanohydroxyapatite to combat teeth sensitivity. EGCG is a micronutrient that is known for its ability to fight Streptococcus mutans bacteria, which form biofilms that cause cavities.The mixture successfully plugged the exposed dentin tubules and prevented the formation of biofilms, New Atlas reported.According to New Atlas, the technology can be used to treat both tooth sensitivity and cavities, possibility in the form of a toothpaste additive.RUNDOWN SHOWS:1. Tooth enamel wears off, exposes dentin; bacteria entering tubules and causing pain in nerves2. EGCG found in green tea can fight Streptococcus mutans bacteria3. EGCG combined with nanohydroxyapatite filled the tubulesVOICEOVER (in English): "Teeth may become sensitive when tooth enamel gets worn off, which exposes the dentin tissue underneath. Food or bacteria that comes into contact with nerve endings through the tubules in dentin tissue is what causes pain.""Scientists have found that a green tea polyphenol known as EGCG can fight Streptococcus mutans bacteria, which is what form biofilms that cause cavities."Researchers combined EGCG with a mineral called nanohydroxyapatite[a]. The mixture successfully plugged exposed dentin tubules, preventing the further erosion."SOURCES: ACS Applied Materials & Interfaces, American Chemical Society, New Atlashttp://pubs.acs.org/doi/abs/10.1021/acsami.7b06597https://www.acs.org/content/acs/en/pressroom/presspacs/2017/acs-presspac-august-2-2017/an-end-to-cavities-for-people-with-sensitive-teeth.htmlhttp://newatlas.com/green-tea-sensitive-teeth/50756/***For story suggestions please contact tips@nextanimation.com.twFor technical and editorial support, please contact:Asia: +61 2 93 73 1841Europe: +44 20 7542 7599Americas and Latam: +1 800 738 8377]]></description>
