      <title>Robotic water snake tracks pollution</title>
      <description><![CDATA[Contact inquiries@nextanimation.com to license this or any News Direct videoFor story suggestions please contact tips@nextanimation.com.twRESTRICTIONS: NONEResearchers in Switzerland have developed a 4-foot-long pollution-tracking robotic water snake.The "Envirobot" comprises several special-purpose modules, which constitute it's eel-like design, according to a press release on the l'cole polytechnique fdrale de Lausanne website. The purpose of the modules are twofold. First, each has a small electric motor that lets the robot swim like a water snake. Secondly, each segment has a unique sensor for gathering different data and measurements. More modules can be added as needed. The robot can swim on a route, or make its own way through a body of water to find the source of pollution, a researcher explains  in the EPFL news release.RUNDOWN SHOWS:1. Envirobot swimming beside a man2. Envirobot modules3. A look at different types of sensors4. More modules being added to envirobotVOICEOVER (in English): "The Envirobot is 4-foot long and comprises several special-purpose modules that constitute it's eel-like design.""The purpose of these modules are twofold. First, each has a small electric motor that lets the robot swim like a water snake. Secondly, each segment has a unique sensor for gathering a variety of data." "For example, biological sensors contain tiny organisms or bacteria that react to the presence of pollutive toxins.""Meanwhile, electrical sensors can track water temperature, and chemical sensors test water acidity.""More modules can be added as needed. The robot can swim on a route, or make its own way through a body of water to find the source of pollution."SOURCES: EPFL, TechCrunch, Inhabitathttps://actu.epfl.ch/news/pinpointing-sources-of-water-pollution-with-a-robo/https://techcrunch.com/2017/07/25/the-envirobot-robo-eel-slithers-along-the-shore-for-science/http://inhabitat.com/this-robotic-eel-hunts-down-the-source-of-water-pollution/***For story suggestions please contact tips@nextanimation.com.twFor technical and editorial support, please contact:Asia: +61 2 93 73 1841Europe: +44 20 7542 7599Americas and Latam: +1 800 738 8377]]></description>
