      <description><![CDATA[Contact inquiries@nextanimation.com to license this or any News Direct videoFor story suggestions please contact tips@nextanimation.com.twRESTRICTIONS: NONESpaceX CEO Elon Musk announced last week that the company would launch its Falcon Heavy rocket in November.Speaking via his official Twitter account, Musk linked to a post on Instagram with a graphic depicting the Falcon Heavy rocket launch and the caption, "Falcon Heavy maiden launch this November."Musk set low expectations for the Falcon Heavy rocket launch last week, saying he does not think it will reach orbit during its debut, Spaceflight Now reported."There's a lot of risk associated with Falcon Heavy, a real good chance that that vehicle does not make it to orbit," Musk said . "I want to make sure to set expectations accordingly."RUNDOWN SHOWS:1. Three SpaceX rockets becoming the Falcon Heavy with payload2. The Falcon Heavy's thrust, side rockets detaching 3. Central rocket delivering payload then returning to Earth4. Central rocket landing beside other rocketsVOICEOVER (in English): "In the first stage of the launch, three re-usable nine-engine cores are used to send the Falcon Heavy into orbit." "Here the rockets use more than 2 million kilograms of thrust, before two detach and return to the launch site.""The central rocket delivers the payload into orbit. "According to SpaceX, the payload can be delivered to points in different levels of orbits." SOURCES: Elon Musk Twitter, Elon Musk Instagram, SpaceX, Engadget, Spaceflight Now,https://twitter.com/elonmusk/status/890765027032039429https://www.instagram.com/p/BXEkGKlgJDK/http://www.spacex.com/falcon-heavyhttps://www.engadget.com/2017/07/28/spacex-falcon-heavy-maiden-flight-november/https://spaceflightnow.com/2017/07/28/musk-sets-november-target-for-debut-of-falcon-heavy/***For story suggestions please contact tips@nextanimation.com.twFor technical and editorial support, please contact:Asia: +61 2 93 73 1841Europe: +44 20 7542