      <description><![CDATA[Visit http://archive.nextanimationstudio.com or contact inquiries@nextanimation.com.tw to license this or any News Direct videoFor story suggestions please contact tips@nextanimation.com.twRESTRICTIONS: NONEGuidelines issued by Guam this month warned residents not to wash with hair conditioner in the event of nuclear attack.This is because conditioner would bind radioactive material to the someone's hair. Meaning that the radioactive material would hang around and become trapped inside follicles.Residents of Guam were instead encouraged under the guidelines to wash with shampoo or soap and water. Shampoo is designed to leave the hair and not remain with it, cosmetics chemist Perry Romanowski explained to NPR.RUNDOWN SHOWS:1. Man using hair conditioner in shower2. Radiation getting into man's hair3. Radiation binding to hair follicles4. Government advice on how to wash with shampooVOICEOVER (in English): "Guidelines issued by Guam this month warned residents not to wash with hair conditioner in the event of nuclear attack.""This is because conditioner is able to bind radioactive material to a person's hair." "Meaning that the radioactive material would hang around and become trapped inside follicles." "Residents of Guam were instead encouraged under the guidelines to wash with only shampoo or soap and water""Unlike conditioner, these are designed to leave the hair and not remain with it." SOURCES: NPR, GUAM HOMELAND SECURITY, READY.GOVhttp://www.npr.org/2017/08/15/543647878/in-the-event-of-a-nuclear-blast-don-t-condition-your-hairhttp://ghs.guam.gov/sites/default/files/files/JIC_Factsheet_2017_003%20-%20In%20Case%20of%20Emergency%20-%20Preparing%20for%20Imminent%20Missile%20Threat.pdfhttps://www.ready.gov/nuclear-blast***For story suggestions please contact tips@nextanimation.com.twFor technical and editorial support, please contact:Asia: +61 2 93 73 1841Europe: +44 20 7542 7599Americas and Latam: +1 800 738 8377]]></description>
