      <description><![CDATA[Visit http://archive.nextanimationstudio.com or contact inquiries@nextanimation.com.tw to license this or any News Direct videoFor story suggestions please contact tips@nextanimation.com.twRESTRICTIONS: NONEThe United States will only have to wait seven years to see another total solar eclipse.The total solar eclipse that passed over the country on Aug. 21 was the first one visible from the contiguous United States since 1979, Time reported.The next total solar eclipse will take place on July 2, 2019. It will be visible from parts of South America and the South Pacific, according to NASA. The next total solar eclipse visible from the United States will take place on April 8, 2024.The paths of the 2017 eclipse and the 2024 eclipse will intersect at Carbondale, Illinois. RUNDOWN SHOWS:1. Depiction of solar eclipse2. Path of 2019 solar eclipse3. Path of 2024 solar eclipse4. Path of 2017 eclipse intersects with 2024 eclipse at Carbondale, IllinoisVOICEOVER (in English): A total solar eclipse occurs when the new moon passes between the sun and the  earth.The next total solar eclipse will take place on July 2, 2019. It will be visible from parts of South America and the South Pacific.The next total solar eclipse visible from the United States will take place on April 8, 2024.The paths of the 2017 eclipse and the 2024 eclipse will intersect at Carbondale, Illinois.SOURCES: NASA, Timehttps://eclipse2017.nasa.gov/what%E2%80%99s-what%E2%80%99s-nexthttp://time.com/4877839/next-total-solar-eclipse-2017-time-path/***For story suggestions please contact tips@nextanimation.com.twFor technical and editorial support, please contact:Asia: +61 2 93 73 1841Europe: +44 20 7542 7599Americas and Latam: +1 800 738 8377]]></description>
