      <description><![CDATA[Visit http://archive.nextanimationstudio.com or contact inquiries@nextanimation.com.tw to license this or any News Direct videoFor story suggestions please contact tips@nextanimation.com.twRESTRICTIONS: NONEThis week at a startup demo convention in Silicon Valley, tech company Flock unveiled a sensor device able to provide homeowners assistance in tracking neighborhood criminals down.Currently installed for testing in seven neighborhoods around Atlanta, Flock's new sensor device records vehicles that enter and pass through the area. Snapshots of all vehicle license plates are taken upon entering and exiting a neighborhood, with plate numbers recorded and stored. According to Flock, the sensor has led to one theft conviction already. The sensor device captured images and the plate number of a man stealing a road bike from a property in a Flock-monitored neighborhood. The BBC reports that future versions of the technology will aim to include facial recognition features.Flock and its new sensor are backed by startup incubator Y Combinator, known for previously funding Reddit, Dropbox, and AirBnB. Following the current trial period, the technology will soon be available to homes for $50 per year.RUNDOWN SHOWS:1. Sensor tracks vehicles entering and exiting neighborhoods2. The software takes photos of vehicles, and records all plate numbers3. Device has already captured a neighborhood bike thief4. Future versions of the sensor will include facial recognitionVOICEOVER (in English): SOURCES: BBC, TechCrunch, DailyTechhttp://www.bbc.com/news/technology-41008141https://techcrunch.com/2017/08/21/y-combinator-summer-2017/http://www.dailytech.com/Do+you+want+to+know+whos+driving+in+your+neighborhood/article42564.htm***For story suggestions please contact tips@nextanimation.com.twFor technical and editorial support, please contact:Asia: +61 2 93 73 1841Europe: +44 20 7542 7599Americas and Latam: +1 800 738 8377]]></description>
