      <title>Why is Houston prone to catastrophic floods?</title>
      <description><![CDATA[Visit http://archive.nextanimationstudio.com or contact inquiries@nextanimation.com.tw to license this or any News Direct videoFor story suggestions please contact tips@nextanimation.com.twRESTRICTIONS: NONELife-threatening floods devastated Houston following record-breaking rainfall from Hurricane Harvey.Houston's proximity to the Gulf Coast makes it susceptible to storms. It's also flat and prone to flooding since the water has nowhere to go, reports Business Insider.The city once had wetlands that acted like sponges to absorb excess water. But urban sprawl meant much of the green spaces have been covered with concrete, which is more water-resistant.There are stormwater drains to catch the flow of rainwater, but these are largely outdated, and cannot handle high volumes.Building regulations in Houston are also not as strict, which leads to many flood-prone residential structures being built in flood zones. Some experts believe climate change may have also worsened Hurricane Harvey. And with worsening weather in our future, Houston's situation emphasizes the need for stricter flood control measures especially in coastal cities.RUNDOWN SHOWS:1. Houston prone to storms and flooding2. Urban sprawl made much of the city unable to absorb excess water3. Storm drains old and outdated4. Building regulations not strictly enforcedVOICEOVER (in English): "Houston's proximity to the Gulf Coast makes it susceptible to storms. It's also flat and prone to flooding since the water has nowhere to go.""The city once had wetlands that acted like sponges to absorb excess water. But urban sprawl meant much of the green spaces have been covered with concrete, which is more water-resistant.""There are stormwater drains to catch the flow of rainwater, but these are largely outdated, and cannot handle high volumes.""Building regulations in Houston are also not as strict, which leads to many flood-prone residential structures being built in flood zones. "SOURCES: